Question 1

The following code calculates the mean gene and protein expression for chimpanzee(chimp) and human for each gene in datasets 143 and 159. The mean chimp gene mRNA and protein for each gene are then plotted against the mean human gene mRNA and protein for each gene. This is done for both data sets. After inspecting these scatter plots, one can see that there is a possible positive relationship between the expression of chimp mRNA levels and human mRNA levels such that it appears that genes expressed at a lower level in chimp are also expressed at a lower level in human. This appears to be true at higher levels of expression as well. However, when looking at protein expression in the two organisms, it appears that there could be a negative linear relationship between amount of protein produced in chimps and humans, but this is not as obvious as with mRNA.

#load data and save, get mean expression for each gene mRNA level and protein level for chimp and human for both data sets
r.143<-read.table(file="TableS3.txt",header=TRUE,sep="\t")
r.159<-read.table(file="TableS4.txt",header=TRUE,sep="\t")

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
chimp.143.rna<-apply(r.143[,3:8],1,mean,na.rm=T)
human.143.rna<-apply(r.143[,9:14],1,mean,na.rm=T)
plot(chimp.143.rna,human.143.rna,xlab="chimp mRNA expression",ylab="human mRNA expression",main="Mean mRNA expression for chimp and human in 143 genes",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.75,pch=20,col="blueviolet")

chimp.143.pr<-apply(r.143[,15:17],1,mean,na.rm=T)
human.143.pr<-apply(r.143[,18:20],1,mean,na.rm=T)
plot(chimp.143.pr,human.143.pr,xlab="chimp protein expression",ylab="human protein expression",main="Mean protein expression for chimp and human in 143 genes",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.75,pch=20,col="blueviolet")

chimp.159.rna<-apply(r.159[,3:8],1,mean,na.rm=T)
human.159.rna<-apply(r.159[,9:14],1,mean,na.rm=T)
plot(chimp.159.rna,human.159.rna,xlab="chimp mRNA expression",ylab="human mRNA expression",main="Mean mRNA expression for chimp and human in 159 genes",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.75,pch=20,col="darkgoldenrod2")

chimp.159.pr<-apply(r.159[,15:17],1,mean,na.rm=T)
human.159.pr<-apply(r.159[,18:20],1,mean,na.rm=T)
plot(chimp.159.pr,human.159.pr,xlab="chimp protein expression",ylab="human protein expression",main="Mean protein expression for chimp and human in 159 genes",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.75,pch=20,col="darkgoldenrod2")

Question 2

The relationship between gene expressed mRNA in chimp and human, as well as protein expression from the same genes were investigated further with correlation. Both pearson correlation values for the relationship between chimp mRNA expression and human mRNA expression show a strong positive relationship exists between the two as both had values that were positive and nearly 1 for both 143 and 159 samples. This indicates that if gene x is expressed weakly in chimp, it is likely also weakly expressed in human. Likewise, if gene y is expressed highly in chimp, it is likely to also be expressed highly in human. On the other hand, the pearson correlation demonstrates a moderate negative relationship between chimp and human protein expression with an r of -.05 for data set 143, while the chimp-human protein relationship in data set 159 is a weaker than in 143 but still negative with an r of -.2. Any relationship between chimp protein expression and human protein expression would be such that an increase in chimp protein for gene x correlates with a decrease in human protein for the same gene.

#Use cor to get pearson correlation coefficient between mean mrna/prot expression per gene, per organism,per sample
cor(chimp.143.rna,human.143.rna)
## [1] 0.9578956
cor(chimp.143.pr,human.143.pr)
## [1] -0.5015678
cor(chimp.159.rna,human.159.rna)
## [1] 0.9574918
cor(chimp.159.pr,human.159.pr)
## [1] -0.2210316

Question 3

The following code fits models to the relationship between gene expressed mRNA in chimp and human, as well as protein expression from the same genes in both chimp and human. This is done for both data sets. In addition, the code outputs diagnostics plots of the fit, shapiro test of normality of residuals and each relationship plotted as a scatter plot with the predicted best fit line.

Results:

  • For all four models, residuals appear fairly normally distributed by histogram and are confirmed to be normally distributed by Shapiro test.

  • The diagnostics plots for both 143 and 159 for chimp and human mRNA means are quite similar. Both demonstrate a qq-plot that indicates a mostly linear relationship as the points are primarily spread along the diagonal line. Some outliers are found at each end, however, that could influence the fit. For both residuals vs.fitted and scale-location plots, the points are evenly distributed along the plot line with the same 3 genes in both data sets being labeled as potential influential outliers. To further evaluate these outliers, we can look at the residuals vs leverage plot and find that while those same 3 genes are implicated as outliers, none of them have particularly high leverage and probably do not require further investigation as they are unlikely to have much influence on the model fit. Overall, diagnostics indicated a good fit for each of these two models. The ANOVA test for model fit confirms that the predicted models for the relationship between chimp and human mRNA are a good fit and that a positive relationship between the two likely exists.

  • The diagnostics plots for both 143 and 159 for chimp and human protein means are also quite similar. Both demonstrate a qq-plot that indicates a mostly linear relationship as the points are primarily spread along the diagonal line. Some outliers are found at each end, however, that could influence the fit. For both residuals vs.fitted and scale-location plots, the points are not well distributed across the plot, with points gathering toward one end of the plot. In residuals vs.fitted plots, the lines do begin to angle for both 143 and 159 data sets, but generally appear to show a linear relationship. For scale-location plots, the points are again gathered to the far right(143) or far left(159) and appear to suggest that the fit of each protein model is non-uniform across the set of predictors. Both residuals vs.fitted and scale-location plots indicate several possible outliers as well, though different genes in the two data sets. To further evaluate these outliers, we can look at the residuals vs leverage plot and find that the same genes are still implicated as outliers in each data set, and two genes in each data set may actually require further investigation as they either have high leverage and are close to being outside cooks distance or are definitely outside cooks distance. Overall, diagnostics indicated that the fit of these two models may be problematic or that the outliers are exerting too much influence. However, the ANOVA test for model fit shows that the predicted models for the relationship between chimp and human mRNA are a good fit and that a negative relationship between the two likely exists.

#fit 4 linear models to the previous means. make dfs first for analysis. plot graphs with regression line and diagnostic plots.
df.143<-data.frame(chimp.rna=chimp.143.rna,human.rna=human.143.rna,chimp.pr=chimp.143.pr,human.pr=human.143.pr)
df.159<-data.frame(chimp.rna=chimp.159.rna,human.rna=human.159.rna,chimp.pr=chimp.159.pr,human.pr=human.159.pr)

rna.model.143<-lm(df.143$human.rna~df.143$chimp.rna,df.143);rna.model.143

Question 5

This code calculates the differences between the mean mRNA expression in humans and chimps for both data sets and the differences between the mean protein expression in humans and chimps for both data sets. The results of protein differences are plotted against mRNA differences for both data sets. Looking at the plots, it appears that there are two completely different relationships between the data sets. In 143, it appears that mRNA expression differences and protein expression differences are negatively associated. In 159, it appears that mRNA and protein differences are positively associated. This does not match what is in Fu et al., 2007. In their study they show both 143 and 159 as having a positive relationship between gene and protein expression differences. In order to reproduce their result, I had to manipulate my calculations of mean differences. Instead of subtracting chimp from human for both mRNA and protein differences (my results), it looks like the authors subtracted chimp from human for the mRNA difference and then switched the order for the protein difference which resulted in a positive relationship(shown in graphs below)!

#find differences in mean rna values between species and mean protein values, plot 
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
#My result 143
rna.diff.143<-human.143.rna-chimp.143.rna
pr.diff.143<-human.143.pr-chimp.143.pr
plot(rna.diff.143,pr.diff.143,xlab="mRNA expression",ylab="protein expression",main="Relationship of 143 mRNA and protein expression differences",col="turquoise4",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.55,pch=1)
#My result 159
rna.diff.159<-human.159.rna-chimp.159.rna
pr.diff.159<-human.159.pr-chimp.159.pr
plot(rna.diff.159,pr.diff.159,xlab="mRNA expression",ylab="protein expression",main="Relationship of 159 mRNA and protein expression differences",col="turquoise4",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.55,pch=1)

#My result 143
rna.diff.143<-human.143.rna-chimp.143.rna
pr.diff.143<-human.143.pr-chimp.143.pr
plot(rna.diff.143,pr.diff.143,xlab="mRNA expression",ylab="protein expression",main="Relationship for 143 found for midterm",col="turquoise4",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.55,pch=1)

#Their result for 143 
Fu.diff.143<-human.143.rna-chimp.143.rna
Fu.pr.diff.143<-chimp.143.pr-human.143.pr
plot(Fu.diff.143,Fu.pr.diff.143,xlab="mRNA expression",ylab="protein expression",main="Relationship for 143 found in Fu et al.,2007",col="turquoise4",cex.lab=.75,cex.main=.55,pch=1)

Question 6

The correlation of mRNA expression differences and protein differences was calculated for each data set below. The correlation confirms what is visualized in the previous section, that there is a moderate negative relationship between mRNA expression and protein expression in the 143 gene data set while there is a weak to moderate positive relationship between mRNA expression and protein expression in the 159 gene data set. Interestingly, when I calculated the correlations based on the manipulation of calculations I showed above, I was able to reproduce the R values shown in Fu et al., 200(both positive correlations).

Question 7

Linear models were calculated to determine the relationship between the mRNA and protein mean differences.

For sample 143, the relationship was a significant negative relationship such that for any increase in the mean difference in mRNA there would be a decrease in the mean difference in protein. Histogram and Shapiro test demonstrate that the residuals are again distributed normally. Qq plot indicates that the residuals display a linear relationship with a few outliers that may influence the overall model fit. For both residuals vs.fitted and scale-location plots, the points are not well distributed across the plot and may indicate a problem with the model fit with sets of points gathering toward one end of the plot, but they generally appear to show a linear relationship. Two outliers are in common to these two plots: NP176 and NP1600. The residuals vs leverage plot demonstrates that the outliers identified in the other two plots are high value residuals but have low leverage which tells us they may not have much influence on the overall model after all. However gene NP1600 has a bit higher leverage and is really close to being outside Cooks distance, so may be worth checking out.

ANOVA analyses of the model indicate that the model is a good fit and confirms the relationship between mRNA and protein expression differences in sample 143.

For sample 159, the relationship was a significant positive relationship such that for any increase in the mean difference in mRNA there would be an increase in the mean difference in protein. Histogram and Shapiro test demonstrate that the residuals are again distributed normally. Qq plot indicates that the residuals display a linear relationship with a few outliers that may influence the overall model fit. For both residuals vs.fitted and scale-location plots, the points are not well distributed across the plot and may indicate a problem with the model fit with sets of points gathering toward one end of the plot, but they generally appear to show a linear relationship. Three outliers are in common to these two plots: NP1809 and NP1822. and NP1600. The residuals vs leverage plot demonstrates that the outliers identified in the other two plots are high value residuals but have low leverage which tells us they may not have much influence on the overall model after all. However gene NP1600 again has a bit higher leverage and is really close to being outside Cooks distance, so may be worth checking out.

ANOVA analyses of the model indicate that the model is a good fit and confirms the relationship between mRNA and protein expression differences in sample 159.

Question 8

This code calculates p-values for t-tests with equal variance assumed on chimp mRNA vs.human mRNA and chimp protein vs.human protein for every single gene in both 143 and 159 samples. Compared to the authors results that found 24 and 23 genes with significantly different mRNA expression in samples 143 and 159, this experiment returned 28 genes with differentially expressed mRNA in sample143 and 29 in sample159. The authors found that there were no genes with significantly different protein expression, but this experiment found that there were 8 genes in both 143 and 159 that were significantly different at the p<.01 level. Histograms of p-values demonstrate that most p-values are widely distributed, supporting the fact that not many genes are expressed differently between chimp and human. One difference in the histograms was that for mRNA more p-values were located toward the 0 end, supporting the fact that I found more significant p-values for mRNA than I did for protein. Scatter plots lack any obvious patterns suggesting a lack of relationship between significance values between protein and mRNA.

m.143.eq<-matrix(0,nrow=nrow(r.143),ncol=4)
colnames(m.143.eq)<-c("rna.pval","pr.pval","r.anova","p.anova")
rownames(m.143.eq)<-rownames(r.143)
m.159.eq<-matrix(0,nrow=nrow(r.159),ncol=4)
colnames(m.159.eq)<-c("rna.pval","pr.pval","r.anova","p.anova")
rownames(m.159.eq)<-rownames(r.159)
count.143.rna<-0
count.143.pr<-0
count.159.rna<-0
count.159.pr<-0
for (i in 1:nrow(r.143)){
  p.rna.143<-t.test(r.143[i,3:8],r.143[i,9:14],var.equal=T,conf.level=.99)
  m.143.eq[i,1]<-p.rna.143$p.value
  if (p.rna.143$p.value<0.01){count.143.rna<-count.143.rna+1}
  p.pr.143<-t.test(r.143[i,15:17],r.143[i,18:20],var.equal=T,conf.level=.99)
  m.143.eq[i,2]<-p.pr.143$p.value
  if (p.pr.143$p.value<.01){count.143.pr<-count.143.pr+1}
}

for (i in 1:nrow(r.159)){
  p.rna.159<-t.test(r.159[i,3:8],r.159[i,9:14],var.equal=T,conf.level=.99)
  m.159.eq[i,1]<-p.rna.159$p.value
  if (p.rna.159$p.value<0.01){count.159.rna<-count.159.rna+1}
  p.pr.159<-t.test(r.159[i,15:17],r.159[i,18:20],var.equal=T,conf.level=.99)
  m.159.eq[i,2]<-p.pr.159$p.value
  if (p.pr.159$p.value<.01){count.159.pr<-count.159.pr+1}
  }
count.143.rna
## [1] 28
count.143.pr
## [1] 8
count.159.rna
## [1] 29
count.143.pr
## [1] 8
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
hist(m.143.eq[,"rna.pval"],col="orange",xlab="mRNA p-values",main="t-test p-value distribution for mRNA")
hist(m.143.eq[,"pr.pval"],col="orange",xlab="protein p-values",main="t-test p-value distribution for protein")
hist(m.159.eq[,"rna.pval"],col="orange",xlab="mRNA p-values",main="t-test p-value distribution for mRNA")
hist(m.159.eq[,"pr.pval"],col="orange",xlab="protein p-values",main="t-test p-value distribution for protein")

plot(m.143.eq[,"rna.pval"],m.143.eq[,"pr.pval"],xlab="mRNA p-values",ylab="protein p-values",main="relationship between mRNA and protein p-values for sample 143",cex.main=.75,cex.lab=.75)
plot(m.159.eq[,"rna.pval"],m.159.eq[,"pr.pval"],xlab="mRNA p-values",ylab="protein p-values",main="relationship between mRNA and protein p-values for sample 159",cex.main=.75,cex.lab=.75)

Question 9

This code repeats the work done in question 8 but with assumed unequal variances. Compared to the authors results that found 24 and 23 genes with significantly different mRNA expression in samples 143 and 159, this experiment returned exactly the same number of genes with differentially expressed mRNA in sample143 and in sample159. The authors found that there were no genes with significantly different protein expression, but this experiment found that there were 3 genes with different protein levels in 143 and 7 in 159 that were significantly different at the p<.01 level. It appears that the study may have incorrectly referenced Students T-test when they referred to it in the paper. The Student t assumes equal variances, and my results using equal variances was different than what was published. However when assuming unequal variances, I was able to capture the same number of differentially expressed genes for mRNA that was published in the study. I believe that the equal variances test is actually more appropriate, as we have the same number of samples for both groups and because inspecting some of the previous linear model diagnostic plots did not reveal any red flag for major differences in variance between chimp and human samples.

In addition, the code below calculates p-values from ANOVA based on linear models of human vs chimp mRNA levels and human vs.chimp protein levels for both samples 143 and 159. These p-values are then compared with the p-values generated from the equal variances t-test as ANOVA assumes equal variances. Scatter plots demonstrate the relationship between p-values, showing that p-values calculated by ANOVA are similar to the p-values from t-tests with equal variances.

m.143<-matrix(0,nrow=nrow(r.143),ncol=4)
colnames(m.143)<-c("rna.pval","pr.pval","ANOVA rna","ANOVA pr")
rownames(m.143)<-rownames(r.143)
m.159<-matrix(0,nrow=nrow(r.159),ncol=4)
colnames(m.159)<-c("rna.pval","pr.pval","ANOVA rna","ANOVA pr")
rownames(m.159)<-rownames(r.159)
count.143.rna<-0
count.143.pr<-0
count.159.rna<-0
count.159.pr<-0
for (i in 1:nrow(r.143)){
  p.rna.143<-t.test(r.143[i,3:8],r.143[i,9:14],conf.level=.95)

chimp.mRNAs <- paste("C",1:6,sep="")
human.mRNAs <- paste("H",1:6,sep="")
chimp.prots <- paste("c",1:3,sep="")
human.prots <- paste("h",1:3,sep="") 
#getting anova pval from linear models 
anova.hc.mRNA <- function(x){
  x.tmp <- x[c(human.mRNAs,chimp.mRNAs)]
  s.tmp <- factor(c(rep("H",length(human.mRNAs)),rep("C",length(chimp.mRNAs))))
  anova(lm(x.tmp~s.tmp))[1,"Pr(>F)"] # get the ANOVA p-value
}

anova.hc.prot <- function(x){
  x.tmp <- x[c(human.prots,chimp.prots)]
  s.tmp <- factor(c(rep("H",length(human.prots)),rep("C",length(chimp.prots))))
  anova(lm(x.tmp~s.tmp))[1,"Pr(>F)"]
}
mRNA.143<-apply(r.143,1,anova.hc.mRNA)
m.143.eq[,3]<-mRNA.143
mRNA.159<-apply(r.159,1,anova.hc.mRNA)
m.159.eq[,3]<-mRNA.159
prot.143<-apply(r.143,1,anova.hc.prot)
m.143.eq[,4]<-prot.143
prot.159<-apply(r.159,1,anova.hc.prot)
m.159.eq[,4]<-prot.159

Questions 10 and 11

This code identifies the genes that are common to samples 143 and 159. It then calculates the mean expression of human mRNA and protein for all those genes in both data sets and for does the same for chimp. Scatter plots are drawn to compare mean human mRNA across 143 and 159, mean human protein across 143 and 159, mean chimp mRNA across 143 and 159, and mean chimp protein across 143 and 159.

This data illustrates a near perfect, if not perfect, linear relationship between sample 143 human mRNA expression levels and sample 159 human mRNA expression levels for the 96 identified shared genes. The same pattern applies to chimpanzee as well. For each of the 96 genes, the scatter plots imply that if gene x is expressed highly in sample 159, it is also expressed as highly in sample 143.

For protein expression, the relationship is less clear. There appears to be a potential negative linear relationship between sample 143 human protein expression levels and sample 159 human protein expression levels for the 96 identified shared genes. Again,the same pattern applies to chimpanzee protein expression between samples.This indicates that if gene x is expressed highly in sample 159, that gene is actually expressed at a lower level in sample 143.

p-value distributions for human mRNA expression between samples 143 and 159 confirm the visual inspection of the scatter plot in that the p-values are all equal to 1.The same distribution of p-values is seen in chimpanzee as well. This confirms that the two samples are not significantly different from each other and would both be drawn from the same population. It is curious that the means for both samples for both chimpanzee and human mRNA were identical with no variation in expression levels. It makes one wonder if the samples were actually the same samples repeated twice.

p-value distributions for human protein expression between samples 143 and 159 show varying levels of p-values, though mostly non-significant ones. The same pattern holds true in chimpanzee.This means that the two samples are not likely significantly different from each other and would be both drawn from the same population.

Question 12b

This is a very basic example showing that ANOVA performed on categorical variable with a continuous variable is comparable to a t-test with equal variances performed on the same data set(because ANOVA assumes equal variances as well.

#set up categorical variable x as male and female and y as continuous variable. Calculate ANOVA from linear model and t-test.
x=c("m","m","m","m","m","f","f","f","f","m")
y=rnorm(10)
z=lm(y~x)
anova(z)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: y
##           Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## x          1  0.1545 0.15448  0.0968 0.7636
## Residuals  8 12.7609 1.59511
t.test(y~x,var.equal=T)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  y by x
## t = -0.3112, df = 8, p-value = 0.7636

Question 12c.

This code shows the comparison of chi-square values generated from the chi-square distribution random sample function and from the normal distribution random sample function. The resulting quantiles are plotted against each other for sample sizes 1, 3 and 10. As we can see, the values do not share a perfectly linear relationship at sample size of 1, indicating that the quantiles dont completely represent samples from the same distribution even though they are both calculated to represent a chi-square distribution. As we increase sample size, we can see that the quantiles match up better and become closer with more points falling on the diagonal line as the sample size increases to 10, indicating that as sample size increases, a chi-square distribution and a normal distribution(changed to a chi-square distribution) are relatively the same.

# Generate 10000 random samples of chi-square with df=1,3 and 10 and calculate a chi square dist from normal dist "by hand". Compare.
#chi square distribution
set.seed(1)
n.sim=10000
rc.1 <- rchisq(n.sim, df=1)
rc.3 <- rchisq(n.sim, df=3)
rc.10 <- rchisq(n.sim, df=10)
#normal distribution,square the values,sum rows for total for samples 1:10000
rn.1<-rnorm(n.sim*1)^2
rn.3<-rowSums(matrix(rnorm(n.sim*3)^2,ncol=3))
rn.10<-rowSums(matrix(rnorm(n.sim*10)^2,ncol=10))
par(mfrow=c(3,2))
qqplot(rc.1,rn.1)
qqplot(rc.3,rn.3)
qqplot(rc.10,rn.10)
